bid(address,uint256[],bool,bytes).details: We use a Dutch auction: price of the assets constantly decreases.The "bidAmounts" array should have equal length as the stored "assetAmounts" array. An amount 0 should be passed for assets the bidder does not want to buy. If the length of "bidAmounts" does not equal "assetAmounts", the function will revert in the Registry.The bidder is not obliged to set endAuction to True if the account is healthy after the bid, but they are incentivised to do so by earning an additional "auctionTerminationReward".If the bidder is a contract, it must implement the IBidCallback interface.

params.account: The contract address of the Account being liquidated.
params.bidAmounts: Array with the assets-amounts the bidder wants to buy.
params.data: Data passed through back to the bidder via the bidCallback() call.
params.endAuction_: Bool indicating that the auction can be ended after the bid.

params.accountFactory: The contract address of the Arcadia Account Factory.
params.sequencerUptimeOracle_: The contract address of the sequencer uptime oracle.

params.account: The contract address of the account in liquidation.

getAuctionInformationArrays(address).details: We need a separate getter functions for the dynamic arrays, since public mappings of structs with dynamic arrays do not returns the arrays.

params.account: The contract address of the Account being liquidated.

returns.assetAddresses: The contract address of each asset in the Account, at the moment the liquidation was initiated.
returns.assetAmounts: The amount of each asset in the Account, at the moment the liquidation was initiated.
returns.assetIds: The ids of each asset in the Account, at the moment the liquidation was initiated.
returns.assetShares: The relative value of each asset in the Account (the "assetShare") with respect to the total value of the Account, at the moment the liquidation was initiated, 4 decimals precision.

getBidPrice(address,uint256[]).details: We use a Dutch auction: price of the assets constantly decreases.The "askedAssetAmounts" array should have equal length as the stored "assetAmounts" array. An amount 0 should be passed for assets the bidder does not want to buy.Only use as off-chain view function! getBidPrice() will not be accurate if the sequencer went down during the auction.

params.account: The contract address of the Account being liquidated.
params.askedAssetAmounts: Array with the assets-amounts the bidder wants to buy.

returns.inAuction: return false when the Account is not being Auctioned.
returns.price: The price for which the bid can be purchased, denominated in the Numeraire.

params.account: The contract address of the Account to be liquidated.

setAccountRecipient(address,address).details: This function can only be called by the Risk Manager of the Creditor.Accounts themselves must never be set as accountRecipient, since ownership transfers of Accounts to themselves will revert. A check on "isAccount()" would not be sufficient to prevent this from happening, since account addresses can be pre-computed before deployment.

params.accountRecipient: The address of the new Account recipient for a given creditor.
params.creditor: The contract address of the Creditor for which the Account recipient is set.

setAuctionCurveParameters(uint32,uint32,.details: The relation between the base and the halfLife time (T_hl): The power function is defined as: N(t) = N(0) * (1/2)^(t/T_hl). Or simplified: N(t) = N(O) * base^t => base = 1/[2^(1/T_hl)].Setting a very short cutoffTime can be used by rogue owners to rug the most junior tranche(s)!! Therefore the cutoffTime has hardcoded constraints.The start price multiplier is a multiplier that is used to increase the initial price of the auction. Since the value of all assets are discounted with the liquidation factor, and because pricing modules will take a conservative approach to price assets (eg. floor-prices for NFTs), the actual value of the assets being auctioned might be substantially higher than the open debt. Hence the auction starts at a multiplier of the openDebt, but decreases rapidly (exponential decay).The minimum price multiplier sets a lower bound to which the auction price converges.All calculations are done with 18 decimals precision.

params.cutoffTime_: The time after which the auction is considered not successful. After the cutoffTime, the remaining assets are transferred to the protocol owner to be sold manually.
params.halfLifeTime: The base is not set directly, but it's derived from a more intuitive parameter, the halfLifeTime: The time T_hl (in seconds with 0 decimals) it takes for the power function to halve in value.
params.minPriceMultiplier_: The minimum price multiplier, with 4 decimals precision.
params.startPriceMultiplier_: The start price multiplier, with 4 decimals precision.

params.sequencerUptimeOracle_: The contract address of the new sequencer uptime oracle.

endAuction(address).notice: Ends an auction and settles the liquidation.

getAuctionInformationArrays(address).notice: Gets the asset arrays from a liquidated Account.

getBidPrice(address,uint256[]).notice: Gets the bid price for amount of assets asked.

liquidateAccount(address).notice: Initiate the liquidation of an Account.

setAccountRecipient(address,address).notice: The Account recipient receives the Accounts after an unsuccessful auction.

setAuctionCurveParameters(uint32,uint32,.notice: Sets the parameters of the auction price curve (decreasing power function).

setSequencerUptimeOracle(address).notice: Sets a new sequencer uptime oracle in the case the current oracle is reverting.
